Could you please provide: Mac version, `MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET` environment value, whether or not you use vanilla XCode and if so `clang --version`, if you used a different compiler (e.g. from homebrew) what that compiler version was?

Was this from a clean `git submodule update --init`-ed repo?

I'm having the same issue.  It is indeed from a clean `git submodule update --init`

$ clang --version
Apple LLVM version 7.3.0 (clang-703.0.31)
Target: x86_64-apple-darwin15.4.0
Thread model: posix
InstalledDir: /Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer/Toolchains/XcodeDefault.xctoolchain/usr/bin

I don't have `MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET` set.  I'm running 10.11.4
I exported `MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=10.11` and got the same result

@jcanizales Thank you for the reference, and has similarities to what I have seen for my client.  Unfortunately I'm not close to a Mac to see determine why the library is not seen in order to resolve the symbols.  What I found for myself is to always comment out out the `cc` reference in my Makefile, so that I force it to use gcc/g++ after every git clone in order to get it to compile on Linux.  This is usually how I do it:

``` Bash
#ifeq ($(HAS_CC),true)
#DEFAULT_CC = cc
#DEFAULT_CXX = c++
#else
ifeq ($(HAS_GCC),true)
DEFAULT_CC = gcc
DEFAULT_CXX = g++
else
ifeq ($(HAS_CLANG),true)
DEFAULT_CC = clang
DEFAULT_CXX = clang++
else
DEFAULT_CC = no_c_compiler
DEFAULT_CXX = no_c++_compiler
endif
endif
#endif
```

Currently, I'm doing a small change to the Makefile to compile without hidden visibility (`-fvisibility=hidden`) to see if that makes a difference.  I might try a few more things, and then put up the issue.

~p
